  "texts": [
    "Examples of one-stage object detection frameworks include the You Only Look Once (YOLO) series [20], YOLOv2 [21], YOLOv3 [22], YOLOv4 [23], YOLOv5 [24], YOLOv6 [25], YOLOv7 [26], YOLOv8 [27], and Single Shot MultiBox Detector (SSD) [28].",
    "The milestones of object detection evolution are shown in Figure 1.",
    "The Strengths and shortcomings of the object detection framework are summarized in Training complexity; Difficulty in detecting small objects; Lack of interpretability; Vulnerability to occlusion and overlapping objects.YOLOV5 [24] Focus structure CSP NetworkFlexibility and ease of use; It achieves real-time or near real-time object detection speeds while maintaining high accuracy.In complex scenes where objects rely heavily on their surroundings or where occlusion is prevalent, the model's performance may be hindered; Training YOLOv5 effectively requires a large and diverse dataset.YOLOV6 [25] EfficientRepThe network design consists of an efficient backbone consisting of RepVGG or CSPStackRep blocks, a PAN topology neck and an efficient decoupling header with a hybrid channel strategy.Not suitable for all scenarios.",
    "In certain specific applications, more specialized algorithms are needed to achieve better performance.",
    "YOLOV7[26] E-ELAN and MPConvYOLOv7 introduces a new scaling strategy for connected models, where the depth and width of blocks are scaled by the same factor to maintain optimal model structure.YOLOv7 introduces a new scaling strategy for connected models, where the depth and width of blocks are scaled by the same factor to maintain optimal model structure.YOLOV8 [27] YOLOv8 CSPDarknet YOLOv8 supports various vision tasks such as object detection, segmentation, pose estimation, tracking and classification.YOLOv8 usually requires a large amount of annotated data for training, especially when dealing with complex scenarios and numerous categories.This can pose challenges for data collection and annotation in certain applications."
